text: hi everyone Anthony Fantana here
internet's busiest music nerd it's a
great day to be alive it's a great day
to be listening to music and this is a
review of the new self-titled fuzz album
fuzz is the collaborative duo of
multi-instrumentalist and garage rock
garage Punk modern garage Punk icon ty
Segall as well as Charlie who Ty has
actually performed with and collaborated
with on numerous occasions the most
recent of which I believe was actually
bringing Charlie on as a guitarist in
the ty Segall band which dropped a
full-length LP last year except Charlie
and and Ty take this LP in a slightly
different direction by embracing some
influences from the worlds of heavy
psyche stoner rock a little bit of
hard-nosed blues rock or classic rock
but the downside is that a lot of the
songs here feel like they could have
really been swapped out and thrown on to
any other ty project and they really
wouldn't have thrown off the track
listing or the flow the album or
anything like that like the opener on
here earth and gate doesn't sound too
unlike many songs from the
slaughterhouse album and honestly it's
not that memorable of a tune either the
intro is overly long when it starts
getting good toward the end it just kind
of fades out and the vintage riffs that
are played throughout this song at a
very high speed while they're not bad
the very chaotic and distorted
production kind of just blurs them all
together and they lose some of their
defining characteristics I think the
only part of the song that really stuck
out to me is being awesome was the
blaring fiery guitar solo that pops in
before the song finishes off there are
other spots though on this LP that come
off as memorable like the really crunchy
riffs on the song sleigh ride
I love the groove that ty and Charlie
hit on this song it really reminds me of
something that could have been on the
Stooges record raw power also the
blaring lead guitars toward the
beginning of the track that are
harmonized in a really odd way it adds a
bit of a quirky characteristic to the
song and the spot-on here
is singing about isolation is one of the
few moments here that are memorable from
a lyrical standpoint these song loose
sutures wasn't a bad moment on here
actually reminded me of an incredibly
extreme version of an old Led Zeppelin
song or two especially when they hit
that distorted peak around the middle
point in the song and there is a huge
drum solo that finishes this track off
and it builds into this really explosive
finish that is maybe one of the most
fantastic points of this album the song
what's in my head is one of the darker
tracks off of this LP and really feels
like ty is borrowing in a huge way from
Black Sabbath especially with the huge
elongated and just overly emphasized
drum fills did it that it and the vocals
on the verse from this track are pretty
melodic as well it's a it's a welcome
change of pace from some of the snotty
and snide and sort of vocals that you
usually hear on other Thai songs that
you usually hear on other songs on this
record while I'm not against the really
raw and aggressive presentation that
Ty's music usually delivers I feel like
a lot of the time he allows that to
overshadow things like finer details and
grandeur and possibly more progressive
ambitions typically ty bringing other
musicians to the table ends up in a
record that is a bit of a standout does
shake things up in his discography a bit
does bring some new elements or just
some newer sounds to the table but maybe
this time it didn't quite happen though
still you know the there is that energy
here there is that ferocity like I said
there are some worthwhile solos and some
great interplay between ty and Charlie
when they focus on that but it feels
like the songwriting sort of fell to the
wayside on this album a bit but if
you've given Fuzzle listen what did you
think of it did you love it hate it why
what do you think I should review next
and that's it Anthony Fantana fuzz
forever
